result.execSummary:
The defendant Alicia T. Borchardt was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Interfere w/ Custody-After Custody Order, a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.31(3)(c).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes:
The defendant shall pay Department of Correction fees as directed by the agent.  Defendant was ordered to report immediately to the probation and parole office.  Case 14CF07 Counts 1,3,5,7,9,11 Misappropriate ID info-Obtain Money; Counts 2,4,6,8,10,12 Bail Jumping Felony were all dismissed and read-in to this case.
Concurrent with: Probation in cases 14CF12, 14CF43, and 14CF39 to run concurrent to each other as are the conditions thereof unless specifically stated.

miscConds.notes: Costs to be paid on a schedule established by the agent.  Defendant is ordered to pay the $250.00 DNA surcharge, provide a sample for testing through the Dept. of Corrections as required in felony convictions.

Defendant is to remain employed/or in school to the agents satisfaction and not change employment/quit school without agents approval, if not employed or in school defendant is to conduct job searches to the satisfaction of the agent.

Defendant shall attend counseling/programing as deemed appropriate by the agent releasing all records to the agent upon request. If defendant is enrolled in counseling sessions per the agent she is not allowed any unexcused absences during these counseling sessions.

The defendant shall have no contact with Matthew Colby  of any kind, whether direct or indirect, including in person, in writing, by phone, by e-mail or other electronic means, through a third party or in any other way. Exception for 3rd party contact for child visitation or exchange. Personal contact exception for attendance at Court Proceedings involving the two parties. Third party contact may be made with Mr Colby by any attorney representing the defendant in regards to legal issues.
  Defendant shall not possess or consume any alcohol, and not go into places that sell alcohol except incidentally such as a grocery store, convenience store or gas station or other such place where alcohol is not sold for consumption on the premises.
Defendant is to maintain absolute sobriety.
  Defendant shall not possess or consume any medication or drug except as may be specifically prescribed by a medical professional for defendant, and then shall be taken only as prescribed.
Defendant is to follow all Family Court orders exactly as they are written.

timeConds.notes: Defendant granted credit for 17 days served and Huber priveleges. Defendant is to report on or before 11-15-2014 at 6pm. Defendant may serve sentence in Langlade County if she can make those arrangements. Privelege of transfer is denied if it results in electronic monitoring.
